	<div class="a-column " id="a-col">
	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-629756 post type-post status-publish hentry category-financial-services category-ipoofferings category-investment-banking category-legal tag-alibaba-group-holding-ltd tag-ally-financial-inc tag-banking-and-financial-institutions tag-citizens-financial-group-inc tag-initial-public-offerings tag-stocks-and-bonds tag-synchrony-financial des-banking-and-financial-institutions des-initial-public-offerings des-stocks-and-bonds org-alibaba-group-holding-ltd-2 org-ally-financial-inc org-citizens-financial-group-inc org-synchrony-financial news_keywords-alibaba news_keywords-ally-financial news_keywords-banking-and-finance news_keywords-citizens-financial-group news_keywords-ipo-2 news_keywords-stocks-and-bonds news_keywords-synchrony-financial" id="post-629756">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/ipoofferings/">I.P.O./Offerings</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Citizens Financial&#8217;s Offering Raises $3 Billion as It Parts From R.B.S.</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Michael J. de la Merced			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-23T22:47:43+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 23, 2014 6:47 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 23, 2014 6:47 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/14/business/dbpix-citizens1/dbpix-citizens1-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/14/business/dbpix-citizens1/dbpix-citizens1-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/14/business/dbpix-citizens1/dbpix-citizens1-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002877620" width="592" height="406" alt="The Citizens Bank Building in Providence, R.I."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="406"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Citizens Bank Building in Providence, R.I.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stew Milne for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/23/citizens-financial-prices-i-p-o-at-21-50-below-expected-range/" data-title="Citizens Financial&#8217;s Offering Raises $3 Billion as It Parts From R.B.S." data-description="The offering tested the appetite of investors for yet another midsize lender, in a year that has seen many seek public listings.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After 26 years within the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/royal-bank-of-scotland-group-plc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Royal Bank of Scotland.">Royal Bank of Scotland</a>, the Citizens Financial Group, the American retail bank, is setting off on its own.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank raised $3 billion in its initial public offering on Tuesday, valuing itself at $12.9 billion, which was below expectations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By pricing the stock sale at $21.50 a share, the lender went below the expected price range of $23 to $25 a share, though a person briefed on the matter said that the order book was significantly oversubscribed at $21.50.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The offering tested the appetite of investors for yet another midsize lender, in a year that has brought many to seek public listings. The stock sale by Citizens was bigger than those of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GE&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about General Electric Company">General Electric</a>âs former consumer finance arm, now known as <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=SYF&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Synchrony Financial">Synchrony Financial</a>; <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/topics/news/business/companies/gmac-llc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Ally Financial.">Ally Financial</a>, the former lending arm of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about General Motors">General Motors</a>; and Santanderâs American <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/your-money/loans/auto-loans/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about auto loans.">auto loan</a> arm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At its I.P.O. price, Citizens will become the second-biggest market debut in the United States this year, behind only the enormous $25 billion stock sale by the Alibaba Group, the Chinese Internet juggernaut.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But just as important, the stock offering is one of the biggest efforts yet by the Royal Bank of Scotland to pay down a government bailout of more than 45 billion pounds (about $73 billion) that it received during the financial crisis, one that left British taxpayers owning about 80 percent of the beleaguered firm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">British regulators have put increasing pressure on the bank, based in Edinburgh, to improve its profitability and slim down its operations. Spinning off Citizens has long been part of the plan to satisfy those concerns.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">R.B.S. is selling about 25 percent of its stake in the American bank through the offering, and plans to sell the rest of its holdings by 2016.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tuesdayâs offering begins the latest chapter of Citizens, which has become one of the countryâs biggest regional banks. Established in 1871, the bank became one of the main lenders in Rhode Island. It was acquired by R.B.S. in 1988.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">According to the I.P.O. prospectus, Citizens had $91.7 billion in deposits and $88.8 billion in loans as of June 30. It earned $479 million in the first half of the year, atop $2.6 billion in total revenue.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Citizens has also come under close scrutiny, particularly after failing part of the Federal Reserveâs stress tests for banks. It has sought to bolster its balance sheet since then, adding more capital to hold in reserve.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is entering the public markets at a time when many lenders have suffered from the twin problems of slow loan growth and low interest rates. Shares in Ally have fallen 2 percent since their debut in April, while those in Santander Consumer have tumbled 29 percent since that companyâs I.P.O. in January.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The financial services sector over all has been among the worst performers in the initial offering market so far this year, with an average total return of minus 1 percent, according to Renaissance Capital, which tracks I.P.O. data and runs a related <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/your-money/investments/mutual-funds-and-etfs/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about mutual funds and exchange-traded funds.">exchange-traded fund</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âEvery time these companies have come out, investors have been told that the economyâs been recovering,â said Kathleen Smith, a principal at Renaissance. âBut itâs been a slow recovery.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, she added, financial companies tend to be among the biggest participants in the I.P.O. market in any given year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Citizens has been preparing for a life as an independent, publicly traded company for some time. It has sought to diversify its operations by bolstering its commercial lending capabilities, while cutting costs and improving offerings ranging from new A.T.M.s to mobile banking apps.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank has also sought to expand its mortgage-lending business to bring it more in line with competitors, even as other firms like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=WFC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Wells Fargo &#038; Company">Wells Fargo</a> are pulling back.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It has also unified its operations across the country, primarily in the Northeast and the Midwest, under the Citizens brand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank will begin trading on the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/n/new_york_stock_exchange/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the New York Stock Exchange.">New York Stock Exchange</a> on Wednesday, under the ticker symbol CFG.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Citizens I.P.O. was led by <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Morgan Stanley">Morgan Stanley</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a>.</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/12/r-b-s-makes-first-move-to-spin-off-citizens/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/14/business/dbpix-citizens1/dbpix-citizens1-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="R.B.S. Makes First Move to Spin off Citizens" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/12/r-b-s-makes-first-move-to-spin-off-citizens/?ref=dealbook">R.B.S. Makes First Move to Spin off Citizens</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By RACHEL ABRAMS</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Its New England banking business, Citizens Financial Group, has filed for an initial public offering in the United States.</p>
			</div>
			
	</div>
